      <h2>What Is AI Visibility?</h2>
      <p>AI visibility measures how likely your website is to be discovered, understood, and cited by AI-powered search engines and assistants. Unlike traditional SEO, which optimizes for Google blue links, AI visibility optimizes for inclusion in generated answers, summaries, and recommendations produced by systems like ChatGPT, Perplexity, Claude, Gemini, and Google AI Overviews.</p>
      <p>These AI systems use specialized crawlers to index the web. GPTBot powers ChatGPT's knowledge. ClaudeBot powers Anthropic's Claude. PerplexityBot feeds Perplexity's real-time search. Google-Extended covers Gemini and Google AI Overviews. If these crawlers cannot access your site, or if your content lacks the structured signals AI systems rely on, your brand simply will not appear in AI-generated answers — even if you rank #1 on traditional Google.</p>
      <p>AI visibility is not replacing SEO. It is an additional layer. The fundamentals — great content, technical health, authority backlinks — still matter. But AI visibility adds new requirements: schema diversity, explicit E-E-A-T markers, AI crawler permissions, and emerging standards like llms.txt that did not exist three years ago.</p>

      <h2>The Five Dimensions We Check</h2>

      <h3>1. AI Crawler Access (20 points)</h3>
      <p>We read your robots.txt file and check whether major AI crawlers are allowed or blocked. A site that blocks GPTBot, ClaudeBot, and PerplexityBot scores poorly here — it is effectively invisible to the AI systems that matter most. We also check for blanket blocks that might inadvertently catch AI crawlers along with malicious bots.</p>

      <h3>2. Structured Data and Schema (20 points)</h3>
      <p>AI systems heavily rely on Schema.org markup to understand what a page is about, who wrote it, when it was published, and how it relates to other content. We check for Article schema, FAQ schema, Organization schema, Breadcrumb schema, and overall schema diversity. Sites with rich, valid schema are far more likely to be accurately cited.</p>

      <h3>3. Content Quality Signals (20 points)</h3>
      <p>AI systems favor substantive, well-structured content. We check content depth (word count), heading structure, title tags, meta descriptions, and canonical tags. Thin pages with no headings and minimal text rarely get cited. Pages with clear hierarchy, comprehensive coverage, and proper technical markup score higher.</p>

      <h3>4. E-E-A-T Signals (20 points)</h3>
      <p>Experience, Expertise, Authoritativeness, and Trustworthiness are critical for AI citation decisions. We check for author bylines, publication dates, About pages, contact information, and social media profiles. AI systems are trained to be cautious — they prefer citing sources that clearly demonstrate who is behind the content and why they are credible.</p>

      <h3>5. AI-Specific Readiness (20 points)</h3>
      <p>This dimension checks emerging standards and practices specifically for AI systems. Does your site have an llms.txt file? Is your sitemap referenced in robots.txt? Do you have diverse schema types covering different content formats? These are the forward-looking signals that will matter more as AI search matures.</p>

